===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|song|lang=enm}}, {{term|sang|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|song|lang=ang}}, {{term|sang||noise, song, singing, chanting; poetry; a poem to be sung or recited, psalm, lay|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|sangwaz||singing, song|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro}} {{recons|sengʷh-||to sing|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|sco|-}} {{term|sang|lang=sco}}, {{term|song||singing, song|lang=sco}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|Song||song|lang=stq}}, {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|sang||song|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|zang||song|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|sang||song|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Sang||singing, song|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|sång||song|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|no|-}} {{term|song||song|lang=no}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{term|söngur||song|lang=is}}, {{etyl|grc|-}} {{term|ὁμφή||voice, stevvon|tr=omphḗ|lang=grc}}. More at {{l|en|sing}}.

